record.title: St James railway station (Building)
record.detail: City Circle line station on the edge of Hyde Park, which was a terminal station for 30 years until the completion of the City Circle with the opening of Circular Quay station in 1956. The station was first planned by JJC Bradfield in his 1915 plan for an electric underground railway loop in the city, but construction was delayed by World War I. Only two of its four tunnels have been used.

record.title: Hyde Park
record.detail: Part of the common land reserved by Governor Phillip for the town's use in 1792, Hyde Park was proclaimed by Macquarie in 1810, and became a racecourse, cricket ground and open space. Without trees until 1854, in later years plantings, civic monuments, paths and buildings were all placed in the park. When the City Circle railway loop was built in the 1920s the whole park was dug up and reconstruction work included planting many of the trees that are still there.

record.title: Archibald fountain
record.detail: The result of a bequest in the will of JF Archibald, the Archibald fountain took 13 years to organise and complete. Its French sculptor François-Léon Sicard never visited the site, which has become one of Sydney's enduring landmarks.

record.title: Transport
record.detail: Sydney's transport has been shaped by the geography of the city, changing economic and social needs, technological limitations and advances, and political considerations. From walking tracks and animal haulage to the commuting city of today, transport has also shaped the city itself, opening up new areas and choking others. Carts, ferries, trains, trams, buses and cars have all figured in Sydney's transport history.

record.title: Cahill Expressway
record.detail: Controversial from its inception, the Cahill Expressway seemed necessary in the 1950s to alleviate city traffic congestion. Repeated calls for its demolition have been unsuccessful.

record.title: Shopping
record.detail: The early colony's closed economy, with limited currency and reliance on government rations, did not foster a retail culture, but it soon developed as the city moved beyond its prison status. At first dealing in necessities of life, Sydney's shops became more elaborate and diverse over time, and as elsewhere, department stores and shopping malls developed new kinds of shopping and consumption.
